comment.narrative: Activities under this outcome are planned for Q3 going forward;

Progress under this outcome is attributed to sensitization on SASA together phase one conducted to Community Activities from 3-sub-Counties of implementation in Kwale (Matuga, Lunga Lunga and Msambweni). SASA together is an approach that supports actions for social change targeting: leaders of organized community groups and associations (youth, men and women) that have an influence on social norms. Second phase of SASA together will be conducted in 2022 as a buildup on the training conducted these years (2021) to equip Cas with knowledge to sensitize community on power dynamics and social norms change in their communities;

The CAs have gotten two important opportunities;- first is to participate in the sub-county anti-GBV working groups in Lunga Lunga, Msambweni and Matuga sub counties and the representation in county stakeholders forum. These two opportunities are pointers to duty bearers appreciating community participation in decision making , and secondly is an opportunity for community voices to reach duty bearers directly.;

comment.narrative: SASA phase 2 sensitization and chain of evidence management sensitization was conducted targeting 28 CAs in Kwale County. emphasis was on the use of power ,understanding power imbalance between men and women and how this power can used positively to achieve gender equality. The under expenditure is because of the savings in the conference package.;

The under expenditure is due to conference package which was slightly cheaper than budgeted. The activity is complete. Under achievement is attributed to 2 CAs dropping out at mobilization level, only 28 CAs were trained . Output was informed by media training of 11-journalists (14 to 24 yrs. - 1-F; 25 to 30 yrs. - 2-F & 1-M & above 30 yrs. - 5-F & 2-M) on gender reporting and sensitization of 28 CAs (20-F; 8-M) on SASA together to equip the CAs with skills and knowledge to lead their communities in retrospective reflection to enhance social norms change; and spark community-wide change and transforming imbalances of power. Over achievement realized under journalists training was as a result of one of the media stations requesting an extra slot to undertake the sensitization.;

comment.narrative: Achievements under this output are informed by preparatory meeting with 7-civil society reps with a participation of 7-Females all above 30 yrs. Also, sensitization on advocacy to 7-civil society entities at National level to determine GYW priority issues & identify advocacy spaces for GYW engagement. A total of 19-GYW participated with 14 to 24 yrs. - 3F, 25 to 30 yrs. - 8F & 2M and above 30 yrs. - 6F. Emerging issues: Retrogressive policies, Harmful traditional practices i.e., Child marriage, inadequate disability inclusive SRH services etc. - formed part of agenda for Sub Activity 2.1.2.1. L&A Sensitization to GYW/ Feminist-led orgs. The budget in PRIMUS is Eur 74 but what we have is Eur 368 for this activity. We spent Eur 309.92;

GEM held the partner kick off meeting, during this meeting strategies were shared and discussion on communication and meaningful youth participation held. It was agreed that the country coordinator would lead in the development of guidelines for meaningful youth participation. GEM also participated in the outcome harvesting workshop where project outcomes were developed and validates as well as the Country annual report. The over-expenditure was occasioned by under budgeting of kick off meeting;

This activity is being informed by the mapping exercise which will provide information CSOs, GYW engagement, interventions capacity needs/ gaps. This information will inform the nature of capacity building to be undertaken. GEM has planned to conduct this activity in Q 3 since after the mapping exercise report has been developed. The target will be achieved after this activity is conducted.;

comment.narrative: Activity implemented here is 2.3.2 which is ongoing with an expenditure as of 30th Sept of Eur 1,499 spent out of Eur 1,624 budget. Activity was conducted jointly at National level in Homabay, Kisumu, Kwale and Nairobi Counties. Conducted to establish baseline information & data on key components including: data on discriminatory gender norms, identify key stakeholders who inform the programmeÃƒÆ’Ã‚Â¢ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â‚¬Å¡Ã‚Â¬ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â‚¬Å¾Ã‚Â¢s objective, identify gaps in implementation coverage, identify areas of linkage & synergies. Respective partners undertook their own mapping in Counties of implementation & consolidated report that were shared with GEM for compilation into one report at the national level. Consolidated draft report is ready.;

Highlights;- GYWs need further support on use of data for advocacy, because of limited knowledge and skills on advocacy. GEM and NAYA will handhold the GYWs when engaging in advocacy to prepare, sharing sources of data, describing data and utilizing it for specific advocacy actions and developing advocacy messages. Information on SRHR is limited, although this was not the focus of the training questions on safe sex, contraceptive and relationships kept emerging and raising a lot of interest form the GYWs. GEM staff were able to answer the questions adequately, it was agreed that SRHR information will be infused in future activities. Over expenditure on air tickets due to high season, hotel due to space and COVID prevention considerations and transport due to more participants.;

Mapping exercise was not completed as planned being that it's a joint activity that needed contribution from all consortium partners. No budget was utilized. Only preparatory activities were conducted in Q2 i.e., development of TOR;

These officials met with GYWs and engaged in discussions on issues that affect the GYWs, from these meetings further engagement on how to address these issues have been agreed on. The over achievements is because we held more meeting than the planned.;

Achievement was attributed to inception meeting conducted with 8 govt. officials; & follow-up meetings conducted with the various Ministries (13 officials) met during inception meeting to further consolidate the areas of synergy earlier discussed the modalities as well for partnership. With this, GEM in partnership with Ministry of youth and ICT enrolled 6 GYWs to be trained as mental health champions. What is in PRIMAS is the budget of Eur 205 for 3.1.2. What we implemented is 3.1.1 which has a budget of Eur 590. We spent Eur 588;

Joint National Inception meeting was conducted jointly with consortium partners. Each partner contributed to the planning process however GEM did not utilize any budget during the joint inception meeting. GEM had two slots of government official representatives to invite; only 1-female attended the meeting (representative from State Department of Gender & Youth affairs);

Under this output, government officials were engaged during the follow up meetings and during the dialogue with key leaders. GEM engaged government officials who they had engaged form the inception meeting.;

description.narrative: Number of (social) media campaigns on impact of negative social gender norms on GYW supported by She Leads partners.

comment.narrative: For this quarter we had planned to hold a webinar to celebrate IWD. This activity was rescheduled to be conducted in April. The fund will be expended in April during the activity.;

GEM as a member of the gender sector working group, was a member of the planning committee for the sixteen days of activism, communications sub committee where messages for social media engagement were developed and approved by stakeholders for use. See attached posters that were developed and approved. We used these messages to engage on social media mainly tweeter. The purpose of the messages was to amplify the voices against GBV in the public domain. We also developed videos with messages with GYWs which we shared online to further amplify the voices of young women against GBV;

No budget was utilized; the budget will be used in Q4. The use of this budget is dependent on the approval of messages by the TdH team. We hope to get approval in time for Dec messaging and the budget will be fully utilized (Ksh.13,000). This was a joint activity where partners were to jointly develop messages & share for approval; and design & print IEC materials for use in social media campaign. This did not work thus GEM's decision to partner with Plan International to commemorate International Youth Day by (1) taking GYW through Inclusion, safeguarding, power dynamics and sustainability concept under She Leads project (2) Utilizing social media platform - GEM Trust Twitter (@GEM_Africa) to push for the theme of the day by retweeting messages.;

Under achievement is due to need to conduct a kickoff meeting which was a prerequisite for implementation of all other activities in the approved work plan, the Menstrual Hygiene Day on 28th May also falls on the day the kick off was ending hence could not be conducted. The International day for the elimination of the sexual violence on 19th June was overtaken by events as all efforts were concentrated on ensuring that the two set up activities were conducted. To ensure that relevant days are commemorated and both financial and programme targets achieved, GEM will commemorate the international youth day and the international day of the girl child.;

The participation entailed-,GYWs presenting their needs to duty bearers e.g the need for registration of GYWs, providing feedback to documents in this case of the CSW engagement during preparation and validation of the Kenya position paper, for the EAC national dialogue GYW were prepared through a session where the bill was unpacked and importance of the bill to GYWs highlighted and gaps and recommendations made. This information is what the GYWs used to engage in the national dialogue.;

The GYWs participated in the disability stakeholders meeting 2.1.2.1. The stake holders meeting is quarterly engagement for advocacy. EAC was conducted in both Q 3 and 4 and UPR in Q 4, hence the expenditure.;
